### 1. Finding Which Bucket an Observation Falls Into

**File:** `/go/agent-index-go/testdata/fixtures/go/prom_histogram.go`, lines 864-897

```go
// findBucket returns the index of the bucket for the provided value, or
// len(h.upperBounds) for the +Inf bucket.
func (h *histogram) findBucket(v float64) int {
    n := len(h.upperBounds)
    if n == 0 {
        return 0
    }
    // Early exit: if v <= first upper bound, return 0
    if v <= h.upperBounds[0] {
        return 0
    }
    // Early exit: if v > last upper bound, return len(h.upperBounds)
    if v > h.upperBounds[n-1] {
        return n
    }
    // For small arrays (< 35 elements), use linear search
    if n < 35 {
        for i, bound := range h.upperBounds {
            if v <= bound {
                return i
            }
        }
        return n
    }
    // For larger arrays, use stdlib binary search
    return sort.SearchFloat64s(h.upperBounds, v)
}
```

This returns the index into `h.upperBounds` (the conventional histogram bucket array). The threshold of 35 was determined empirically — below that, linear search is faster than binary search on real hardware.

